      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Also"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "180g soft dates"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "1 teaspoon bicarbonate soda"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Grease a fairly deep 1.2 Litre baking dish with butter.  Place the dates in a heatproof bowl with the bicarbonate of soda and stir.  Pour over the boiling water, cover the bowl with cling film and leave the dates to soak for around 30 minutes before mashing the dates with a fork to a pulp.  Set aside while you make the sponge.  Preheat the oven to 180C/160 Fan/350F/Gas mark 4."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Using an electric mixer or wooden spoon, cream the soft butter and sugar together for about 5 minutes or until very light and fluffy.  Beat in the eggs, a little at a time, waiting until they are fully incorporated before adding the rest. Beat in the vanilla extract, treacle and golden syrup."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Fold in half the flour, folding lightly until no streaks of flour can be seen.  Fold in half the milk, then repeat with the remaining flour and milk.  Stir the mashed dates and any remaining liquid into the batter until smooth.  The batter will look like a curdled mess at this point, but don’t worry."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pour the batter into the greased tin and bake for 40-50 minutes or until the pudding has risen, is springy to the touch and a skewer inserted in the middle of the cake emerges with no raw batter clinging to it.  A little stickiness is fine!"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "While the sponge is baking, make the sauce.  Melt the sugar, butter and treacle in a large saucepan over a low heat. Once the butter has melted and the sugar has dissolved, stir in the cream.  Turn the heat up slightly and when the sauce is bubbling remove from the heat.  Cover to keep warm."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "As soon as the pudding is out of the oven, skewer it all over with a cocktail stick or cake tester and pour over about half of the sauce, allowing it to soak into the sponge.  Using a spatula, spread the sauce to the edges so the entire sponge is covered in the sauce."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leave the pudding to stand for about 30 minutes before serving with ice cream, double cream or custard, and the remaining toffee sauce."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Ultimate Chocolate Cake"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
